You are given a program that already exists, and a tree that no longer contains one of
the nodes that produced it. Make the smallest change to the program that the removal
forces, and no other change.

You are not writing this program. It is written. You are removing one thing from it.

Every line the remaining tree still implies survives, character for character,
including its indentation and its blank lines around it. Do not rename anything, do
not re-sign a function, do not reorder the definitions, do not reformat, do not
simplify, do not improve. If a line would have been written the same way by a
programmer who never saw the deleted node, that line stays exactly as it is.

Remove exactly what the deleted node was holding up, and repair only what breaks when
it goes: a call with no callee, a name with no binding.

If the deleted node was holding nothing up, the correct answer is the program back
unchanged, byte for byte. That is a common and correct answer, and it is never a
failure to return it.
